title: For Sale:  New Engraved 1861 Colt Navy Presentation Revolver
postcontent: Priced Reduced.....All Reasonable Offers Considered **************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************** The letter from Colt has finally arrived. In order to reveal the content of the letter I have added two photos to this auction (see photos #32 & 33). **************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************** Fully Engraved 1861 Colt Navy presentation Revolver 36 caliber, very early serial number 9765. I am selling this gun on consignment. It is out of an old Indian Trading Post from Gallup, New Mexico where it has been stored in a vault for over 25 years. This gun is in superb (museum quality) condition. The gun is silver plated and fully engraved by Gustave Young who was Colt's premier engraver from the 1850s through the 1870s. He is often referred to as the Picasso of engravers. His "signature" mark is the dog/wolf head show here in photo #24. The gun's grips are ivory and it has all matching serial numbers. This gun was obviously a custom order gun made as a presentation piece. The back of the back strap was left blank where a persons name would have been engraved (see photo #29). I have been told the Confederacy ordered a small number of these Navy models at the beginning of the civil war to be used as presentation pieces. Because the serial number fits in that same time period it has been suggested that this could very well be one of those pieces? While we know very little about the history of this gun we do know it is extremely rare to find a silver plated Gustave Young engraved presentation gun for sale in this kind of condition. The gun is being offered with an on site inspection and approval by the buyer. It can be shipped registered mail but only after the sellers approval and payment has been made. ONLY SERIOUS BUYERS SHOULD CONTACT ME PLEASE

postcontent:
Selling my Redfield Battlezone 3-9x42 scope with MOA reticle and turrets. It was attached to my BCM 20" upper but sold that to a friend who wanted to put his Leupold Mk 4 on it (I dont blame him).

The scope has seen minimal range trips, mainly to get sighted in and than to go ring steel no more than a handful of times. I cant speak to the 308 turret (which comes with the scope) but the 556 turret was spot on with the BDC markings. I was never able to test it out to 500yds, but at 400yds it was spot on hitting 12" ringers.

I am including the Leupold Mk2 IMS 1" one-piece mount (with packaging) since everything has been leveled and torqued down (had the scope installed by a gunsmith). I took it on and off the 20" upper a couple times to see if it would hold zero with the mount and as far as I could tell (shooting out to 200yds) it did a great job as long as you got it back on the correct rail slots.

Hope to hear back from you soon, and dont hesitate to ask questions.
Thanks.
Huey Na

PS, eyepiece WILL clear a Magpul MBUS rear sight but barely. That was the one thing that I wanted the scope to do (low on the rifle as much as possible and not have to take off my backup sights.

I am in Wake County.
Price: $1,500 (firm).  I am not looking for any trades at this tim
Interested parties can reach me at: [email]REDACTED[/email]

This rifle comes as you see it here and will ship in its original Springfield Armory factory box.
Specifications:
- This is a Springfield Armory "Loaded" model M1A
- It comes with 2 stocks:  A USGI walnut stock and a USGI Fiberglass stock.
- 2-stage match grade trigger.
- National Match front sight blade.
- Match Grade rear aperture with 1/2 MOA windage adjustments.  Bore and barrel are in excellent condition.
- Stainless steel 22" National Match barrel (labeled "NM .308 SS")
- It has an upgraded GI extractor and spring
- 12x 20-round magazines, blued (New manufacture, Like new condition) ($240 value)
- 1x 10-round factory magazine with parkerized finish
- Magazine pouch for the buttstock ($20 value)
- Cleaning kit inside buttstock ($20 value)
- M14 GI sling, nylon

The first owner of this rifle bought it to hunt with. He soon realized that a Battle Rifle is not necessarily an ideal deer rifle. :-) That is when he sold it to me. He had very few rounds through it. I have had this rifle for almost 7 years. I have put approximately 800 rounds through it. I added the GI extractor, mag pouch, and cleaning kit. I also painted in the numbers on dials of the rear sight so you can read the elevation and windage markings clearly.

Someone asked me how far out I have shot it.
I have shot it out to 500 yards. When I am doing my part, it shoots 2-3 moa with NATO mil-surp ammo. It will do better with Hornady 165gr SST or Federal Gold Match 168gr ammo.  With South African Nato 7.62x51 ammo, the rifle is dead-balls-on at 200, 300, 400, and 500 yards. You just gotta dial it in and do your part... and it hits where it should. 

The elevation knob does go to 1000 as I recall. It would be really cool to take it up to Camp Butner and see what she will do out to 1000 yards. It might be a lot to ask of a 147 grain mil-spec projectile... but the 168 Federal Gold Match round was made with the M1A in mind and it will get it done.

NOTE:
Only serious inquiries, please.
All local, state, & federal laws apply. That means that I will not sell to your brother to give to you so please do not even ask for a strawman purchase.

postcontent:
For sale or trade: -1929 Izhevsk Hex receiver Mosin Nagant m91/30 Rifle - 7.62x54R-
A fun plinking rifle with a battle proven history, and the best part? You don't have to clean out the nasty cosmoline, because I've done it for you.  I've taken good care of this gun, and cleaned it thoroughly after shooting corrosive surplus. 

The rifle is in good shape for being 85 years old and being issued if not used in combat, and was clearly refinished some prior to being packed away for decades.  Matching numbers on all of the major parts, and came out of the box shooting close to point of aim at 100 yards with 147/150 grain ammo.  I am pretty sure this is an ex-dragoon. This is indeed a hex receiver, the picture indicating the 1929 date doesn't show the hexagonal portion. This specimen is not counterbored, although the rifling at the muzzle does have some wear.  The rifling, like most Mosins, is dark and frosted but solid.  There is minor surface wear on the wood from the barrel bands, and there is bluing wear along where the bayonet attaches.  I have used this gun to plink and deer hunt, and am selling because I recently bought a 308 Savage.

Also included:
Ammo: 682 Rounds of 1975mfg silver tipped Russian surplus ammo (corrosive), and 43 brass PPU 150 grain softpoints (+17 brass cases.)  Comes with wooden crate, can opener (1 spam can still sealed.)
